# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcc-internals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language usually has one statement per machine code instruction (1:1), but constants, comments, assembler directives, symbolic labels of, e.g., memory locations, registers, and macros are generally also supported.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The first assembly code in which a language is used to represent machine code instructions is found in Kathleen and Andrew Donald Booth's 1947 work, *Coding for A.R.C.*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembly code is converted into executable machine code by a utility program referred to as an *assembler*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The term "assembler" is generally attributed to Wilkes, Wheeler and Gill in their 1951 book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, who, however, used the term to mean "a program that assembles another program consisting of several sections into a single program".
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The conversion process is referred to as *assembly*, as in *assembling* the source code.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The computational step when an assembler is processing a program is called *assembly time*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Because assembly depends on the machine code instructions, each assembly language is specific to a particular computer architecture such as x86 or ARM.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes there is more than one assembler for the same architecture, and sometimes an assembler is specific to an operating system or to particular operating systems.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Most assembly languages do not provide specific syntax for operating system calls, and most assembly languages can be used universally with any operating system, as the language provides access to all the real capabilities of the processor, upon which all system call mechanisms ultimately rest.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In contrast to assembly languages, most high-level programming languages are generally portable across multiple architectures but require interpreting or compiling, much more complicated tasks than assembling.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In the first decades of computing, it was commonplace for both systems programming and application programming to take place entirely in assembly language.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] While still irreplaceable for some purposes, the majority of programming is now conducted in higher-level interpreted and compiled languages.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In "No Silver Bullet", Fred Brooks summarised the effects of the switch away from assembly language programming: "Surely the most powerful stroke for software productivity, reliability, and simplicity has been the progressive use of high-level languages for programming.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Today, it is typical to use small amounts of assembly language code within larger systems implemented in a higher-level language, for performance reasons or to interact directly with hardware in ways unsupported by the higher-level language.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] For instance, just under 2% of version 4.9 of the Linux kernel source code is written in assembly; more than 97% is written in C.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language uses mnemonic symbols to represent low-level machine instructions (opcodes), directives, and usually architectural registers and flags.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some of the mnemonics may be built-in and some user-defined.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Many operations require one or more operands in order to form a complete instruction.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers permit named constants, registers, and labels for program and memory locations, and can calculate expressions for operands.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Thus, programmers are freed from tedious repetitive calculations and assembler programs are much more readable than machine code.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Depending on the architecture, these elements may also be combined for specific instructions or addressing modes using offsets or other data as well as fixed addresses.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers offer additional mechanisms to facilitate program development, to control the assembly process, and to aid debugging.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some are column oriented, with specific fields in specific columns; this was very common for machines using punched cards in the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers have free-form syntax, with fields separated by delimiters, e.g., punctuation, white space.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers are hybrid, with, e.g., labels, in a specific column and other fields separated by delimiters; this became more common than column-oriented syntax in the 1960s.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] An **assembler** program creates object code by translating combinations of mnemonics and syntax for operations and addressing modes into their numerical equivalents.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This representation typically includes an *operation code* ("opcode") as well as other control bits and data.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The assembler also calculates constant expressions and resolves symbolic names for memory locations and other entities.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The use of symbolic references is a key feature of assemblers, saving tedious calculations and manual address updates after program modifications.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers also include macro facilities for performing textual substitution – e.g., to generate common short sequences of instructions as inline, instead of *called* subroutines.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers may also be able to perform some simple types of instruction set-specific optimizations.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] One concrete example of this may be the ubiquitous x86 assemblers from various vendors.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Called jump-sizing, most of them are able to perform jump-instruction replacements (long jumps replaced by short or relative jumps) in any number of passes, on request.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Others may even do simple rearrangement or insertion of instructions, such as some assemblers for RISC architectures that can help optimize a sensible instruction scheduling to exploit the CPU pipeline as efficiently as possible.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assemblers have been available since the 1950s, as the first step above machine language and before high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Algol, COBOL and Lisp.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] There have also been several classes of translators and semi-automatic code generators with properties similar to both assembly and high-level languages, with Speedcode as perhaps one of the better-known examples.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] There may be several assemblers with different syntax for a particular CPU or instruction set architecture.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] For instance, an instruction to add memory data to a register in a x86-family processor might be `add eax,[ebx]`, in original *Intel syntax*, whereas this would be written `addl (%ebx),%eax` in the *AT&T syntax* used by the GNU Assembler.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Despite different appearances, different syntactic forms generally generate the same numeric machine code.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] A single assembler may also have different modes in order to support variations in syntactic forms as well as their exact semantic interpretations (such as FASM-syntax, TASM-syntax, ideal mode, etc., in the special case of x86 assembly programming).
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] There are two types of assemblers based on how many passes through the source are needed (how many times the assembler reads the source) to produce the object file.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In both cases, the assembler must be able to determine the size of each instruction on the initial passes in order to calculate the addresses of subsequent symbols.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In an assembler with peephole optimization, addresses may be recalculated between passes to allow replacing pessimistic code with code tailored to the exact distance from the target.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The original reason for the use of one-pass assemblers was memory size and speed of assembly – often a second pass would require storing the symbol table in memory (to handle forward references), rewinding and rereading the program source on tape, or rereading a deck of cards or punched paper tape.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Later computers with much larger memories (especially disc storage), had the space to perform all necessary processing without such re-reading.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The advantage of the multi-pass assembler is that the absence of errata makes the linking process (or the program load if the assembler directly produces executable code) faster.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] See Language design below for more details.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] A program written in assembly language consists of a series of mnemonic processor instructions and meta-statements (known variously as declarative operations, directives, pseudo-instructions, pseudo-operations and pseudo-ops), comments and data.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language instructions usually consist of an opcode mnemonic followed by an operand, which might be a list of data, arguments or parameters.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some instructions may be "implied", which means the data upon which the instruction operates is implicitly defined by the instruction itself—such an instruction does not take an operand.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The resulting statement is translated by an assembler into machine language instructions that can be loaded into memory and executed.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] For example, the instruction below tells an x86/IA-32 processor to move an immediate 8-bit value into a register.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The binary code for this instruction is 10110 followed by a 3-bit identifier for which register to use.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The identifier for the *AL* register is 000, so the following machine code loads the *AL* register with the data 01100001.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This binary computer code can be made more human-readable by expressing it in hexadecimal as follows.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Here, `B0` means "Move a copy of the following value into *AL*", and `61` is a hexadecimal representation of the value 01100001, which is 97 in decimal.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language for the 8086 family provides the mnemonic MOV (an abbreviation of *move*) for instructions such as this, so the machine code above can be written as follows in assembly language, complete with an explanatory comment if required, after the semicolon.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This is much easier to read and to remember.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Other assemblers may use separate opcode mnemonics such as L for "move memory to register", ST for "move register to memory", LR for "move register to register", MVI for "move immediate operand to memory", etc.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] If the same mnemonic is used for different instructions, that means that the mnemonic corresponds to several different binary instruction codes, excluding data (e.g. the `61h` in this example), depending on the operands that follow the mnemonic.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] For example, for the x86/IA-32 CPUs, the Intel assembly language syntax `MOV AL, AH` represents an instruction that moves the contents of register *AH* into register *AL*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The first byte, 88h, identifies a move between a byte-sized register and either another register or memory, and the second byte, E0h, is encoded (with three bit-fields) to specify that both operands are registers, the source is *AH*, and the destination is *AL*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In a case like this where the same mnemonic can represent more than one binary instruction, the assembler determines which instruction to generate by examining the operands.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In the first example, the operand `61h` is a valid hexadecimal numeric constant and is not a valid register name, so only the `B0` instruction can be applicable.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In the second example, the operand `AH` is a valid register name and not a valid numeric constant (hexadecimal, decimal, octal, or binary), so only the `88` instruction can be applicable.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages are always designed so that this sort of lack of ambiguity is universally enforced by their syntax.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] For example, in the Intel x86 assembly language, a hexadecimal constant must start with a numeral digit, so that the hexadecimal number 'A' (equal to decimal ten) would be written as `0Ah` or `0AH`, not `AH`, specifically so that it cannot appear to be the name of register *AH*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Returning to the original example, while the x86 opcode 10110000 (`B0`) copies an 8-bit value into the *AL* register, 10110001 (`B1`) moves it into *CL* and 10110010 (`B2`) does so into *DL*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language examples for these follow.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The syntax of MOV can also be more complex as the following examples show.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In each case, the MOV mnemonic is translated directly into one of the opcodes 88-8C, 8E, A0-A3, B0-BF, C6 or C7 by an assembler, and the programmer normally does not have to know or remember which.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] An assembler transforms assembly language into machine code, and the reverse can at least partially be achieved by a disassembler.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Unlike high-level languages, there is a one-to-one correspondence between many simple assembly statements and machine language instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] However, in some cases, an assembler may provide *pseudoinstructions* (essentially macros) which expand into several machine language instructions to provide commonly needed functionality.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] For example, for a machine that lacks a "branch if greater or equal" instruction, an assembler may provide a pseudoinstruction that expands to the machine's "set if less than" and "branch if zero (on the result of the set instruction)".
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Most full-featured assemblers also provide a rich macro language (discussed below) which is used by vendors and programmers to generate more complex code and data sequences.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Likewise, since comments in the assembly language source file are ignored by the assembler and have no effect on the object code it generates, a disassembler is always completely unable to recover source comments.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Each computer architecture has its own machine language.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Computers differ in the number and type of operations they support, in the different sizes and numbers of registers, and in the representations of data in storage.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] While most general-purpose computers are able to carry out essentially the same functionality, the ways they do so differ; the corresponding assembly languages reflect these differences.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Multiple sets of mnemonics or assembly-language syntax may exist for a single instruction set, typically instantiated in different assembler programs.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In these cases, the most popular one is usually that supplied by the CPU manufacturer and used in its documentation.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Two examples of CPUs that have two different sets of mnemonics are the Intel 8080 family and the Intel 8086/8088.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Because Intel claimed copyright on its assembly language mnemonics (on each page of their documentation published in the 1970s and early 1980s, at least), some companies that independently produced CPUs compatible with Intel instruction sets invented their own mnemonics.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The Zilog Z80 CPU, an enhancement of the Intel 8080A, supports all the 8080A instructions plus many more; Zilog invented an entirely new assembly language, not only for the new instructions but also for all of the 8080A instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] For example, where Intel uses the mnemonics *MOV*, *MVI*, *LDA*, *STA*, *LXI*, *LDAX*, *STAX*, *LHLD*, and *SHLD* for various data transfer instructions, the Z80 assembly language uses the mnemonic *LD* for all of them.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] A similar case is the NEC V20 and V30 CPUs, enhanced copies of the Intel 8086 and 8088, respectively.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Like Zilog with the Z80, NEC invented new mnemonics for all of the 8086 and 8088 instructions, to avoid accusations of infringement of Intel's copyright.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] "Hello, world!" can be printed using 32-bit assembly language for an x86 processor with little help from an operating system.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] "Call outchr" calls some mechanism that prints a character in AL to the console.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] A non zero-length string must be terminated with a byte of zero.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] There is a large degree of diversity in the way the authors of assemblers categorize statements and in the nomenclature that they use.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In particular, some describe anything other than a machine mnemonic or extended mnemonic as a pseudo-operation (pseudo-op).
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Instructions (statements) in assembly language are generally very simple, unlike those in high-level languages.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Generally, a mnemonic is a symbolic name for a single executable machine language instruction (an opcode), and there is at least one opcode mnemonic defined for each machine language instruction.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Each instruction typically consists of an *operation* or *opcode* plus zero or more *operands*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Most instructions refer to a single value or a pair of values.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Operands can be immediate (value coded in the instruction itself), registers specified in the instruction or implied, or the addresses of data located elsewhere in storage.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This is determined by the underlying processor architecture: the assembler merely reflects how this architecture works.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] *Extended mnemonics* are often used to specify a combination of an opcode with a specific operand, e.g., the System/360 assemblers use `B` as an extended mnemonic for `BC` with a mask of 15 and `NOP` ("NO OPeration" – do nothing for one step) for `BC` with a mask of 0.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers also support simple built-in macro-instructions that generate two or more machine instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] For instance, with some Z80 assemblers the instruction `ld hl,bc` is recognized to generate `ld l,c` followed by `ld h,b`.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] These are sometimes known as *pseudo-opcodes*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Mnemonics are arbitrary symbols; in 1985 the IEEE published Standard 694 for a uniform set of mnemonics to be used by all assemblers.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] There are instructions used to define data elements to hold data and variables.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] They define the type of data, the length and the alignment of data.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] These instructions can also define whether the data is available to outside programs (programs assembled separately) or only to the program in which the data section is defined.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers classify these as pseudo-ops.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembly directives, also called pseudo-opcodes, pseudo-operations or pseudo-ops, are commands given to an assembler "directing it to perform operations other than assembling instructions".
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Directives affect how the assembler operates and "may affect the object code, the symbol table, the listing file, and the values of internal assembler parameters".
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes the term *pseudo-opcode* is reserved for directives that generate object code, such as those that generate data.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The names of pseudo-ops often start with a dot to distinguish them from machine instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Pseudo-ops can make the assembly of the program dependent on parameters input by a programmer, so that one program can be assembled in different ways, perhaps for different applications.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Or, a pseudo-op can be used to manipulate presentation of a program to make it easier to read and maintain.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Another common use of pseudo-ops is to reserve storage areas for run-time data and optionally initialize their contents to known values.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Symbolic assemblers let programmers associate arbitrary names (*labels* or *symbols*) with memory locations and various constants.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Usually, every constant and variable is given a name so instructions can reference those locations by name, thus promoting self-documenting code.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In executable code, the name of each subroutine is associated with its entry point, so any calls to a subroutine can use its name.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Inside subroutines, GOTO destinations are given labels.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers support *local symbols* which are often lexically distinct from normal symbols (e.g., the use of "10$" as a GOTO destination).
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers, such as NASM, provide flexible symbol management, letting programmers manage different namespaces, automatically calculate offsets within data structures, and assign labels that refer to literal values or the result of simple computations performed by the assembler.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Labels can also be used to initialize constants and variables with relocatable addresses.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages, like most other computer languages, allow comments to be added to program source code that will be ignored during assembly.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Judicious commenting is essential in assembly language programs, as the meaning and purpose of a sequence of binary machine instructions can be difficult to determine.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The "raw" (uncommented) assembly language generated by compilers or disassemblers is quite difficult to read when changes must be made.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers support *predefined macros*, and others support *programmer-defined* (and repeatedly re-definable) macros involving sequences of text lines in which variables and constants are embedded.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The macro definition is most commonly a mixture of assembler statements, e.g., directives, symbolic machine instructions, and templates for assembler statements.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This sequence of text lines may include opcodes or directives.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Once a macro has been defined its name may be used in place of a mnemonic.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] When the assembler processes such a statement, it replaces the statement with the text lines associated with that macro, then processes them as if they existed in the source code file (including, in some assemblers, expansion of any macros existing in the replacement text).
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Macros in this sense date to IBM autocoders of the 1950s.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In assembly language, the term "macro" represents a more comprehensive concept than it does in some other contexts, such as the pre-processor in the C programming language, where its #define directive typically is used to create short single line macros.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembler macro instructions, like macros in PL/I and some other languages, can be lengthy "programs" by themselves, executed by interpretation by the assembler during assembly.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Since macros can have 'short' names but expand to several or indeed many lines of code, they can be used to make assembly language programs appear to be far shorter, requiring fewer lines of source code, as with higher level languages.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] They can also be used to add higher levels of structure to assembly programs, optionally introduce embedded debugging code via parameters and other similar features.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Macro assemblers often allow macros to take parameters.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Thus a macro might generate numerous assembly language instructions or data definitions, based on the macro arguments.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This could be used to generate record-style data structures or "unrolled" loops, for example, or could generate entire algorithms based on complex parameters.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] For instance, a "sort" macro could accept the specification of a complex sort key and generate code crafted for that specific key, not needing the run-time tests that would be required for a general procedure interpreting the specification.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] An organization using assembly language that has been heavily extended using such a macro suite can be considered to be working in a higher-level language since such programmers are not working with a computer's lowest-level conceptual elements.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Underlining this point, macros were used to implement an early virtual machine in SNOBOL4 (1967), which was written in the SNOBOL Implementation Language (SIL), an assembly language for a virtual machine.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The target machine would translate this to its native code using a macro assembler.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This allowed a high degree of portability for the time.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Macros were used to customize large scale software systems for specific customers in the mainframe era and were also used by customer personnel to satisfy their employers' needs by making specific versions of manufacturer operating systems.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] IBM OS/360 uses macros to perform system generation.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The user specifies options by coding a series of assembler macros.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Assembling these macros generates a job stream to build the system, including job control language and utility control statements.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This is because, as was realized in the 1960s, the concept of "macro processing" is independent of the concept of "assembly", the former being in modern terms more word processing, text processing, than generating object code.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The concept of macro processing appeared, and appears, in the C programming language, which supports "preprocessor instructions" to set variables, and make conditional tests on their values.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Unlike certain previous macro processors inside assemblers, the C preprocessor is not Turing-complete because it lacks the ability to either loop or "go to", the latter allowing programs to loop.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Despite the power of macro processing, it fell into disuse in many high level languages (major exceptions being C, C++ and PL/I) while remaining a perennial for assemblers.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Macro parameter substitution is strictly by name: at macro processing time, the value of a parameter is textually substituted for its name.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The most famous class of bugs resulting was the use of a parameter that itself was an expression and not a simple name when the macro writer expected a name.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] the intention was that the caller would provide the name of a variable, and the "global" variable or constant b would be used to multiply "a".
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] If foo is called with the parameter `a-c`, the macro expansion of `load a-c*b` occurs.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] To avoid any possible ambiguity, users of macro processors can parenthesize formal parameters inside macro definitions, or callers can parenthesize the input parameters.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Packages of macros have been written providing structured programming elements to encode execution flow.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The earliest example of this approach was in the Concept-14 macro set, originally proposed by Harlan Mills (March 1970), and implemented by Marvin Kessler at IBM's Federal Systems Division, which provided IF/ELSE/ENDIF and similar control flow blocks for OS/360 assembler programs.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This was a way to reduce or eliminate the use of GOTO operations in assembly code, one of the main factors causing spaghetti code in assembly language.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] This approach was widely accepted in the early 1980s (the latter days of large-scale assembly language use).
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] IBM's High Level Assembler Toolkit includes such a macro package.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Another design was A-Natural, a "stream-oriented" assembler for 8080/Z80 processors from Whitesmiths Ltd.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] (developers of the Unix-like Idris operating system, and what was reported to be the first commercial C compiler).
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] The language was classified as an assembler because it worked with raw machine elements such as opcodes, registers, and memory references; but it incorporated an expression syntax to indicate execution order.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] Parentheses and other special symbols, along with block-oriented structured programming constructs, controlled the sequence of the generated instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] A-natural was built as the object language of a C compiler, rather than for hand-coding, but its logical syntax won some fans.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] There has been little apparent demand for more sophisticated assemblers since the decline of large-scale assembly language development.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p01] In spite of that, they are still being developed and applied in cases where resource constraints or peculiarities in the target system's architecture prevent the effective use of higher-level languages.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] When the stored-program computer was introduced, programs were written in machine code, and loaded into the computer from punched paper tape or toggled directly into memory from console switches.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] In late 1948, the Electronic Delay Storage Automatic Calculator (EDSAC) had an assembler (named "initial orders") integrated into its bootstrap program.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] It used one-letter mnemonics developed by David Wheeler, who is credited by the IEEE Computer Society as the creator of the first "assembler".
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Reports on the EDSAC introduced the term "assembly" for the process of combining fields into an instruction word.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] SOAP (Symbolic Optimal Assembly Program) was an assembly language for the IBM 650 computer written by Stan Poley in 1955.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Assembly languages eliminated much of the error-prone, tedious, and time-consuming first-generation programming needed with the earliest computers, freeing programmers from tedium such as remembering numeric codes and calculating addresses.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] They were once widely used for all sorts of programming.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] By the late 1950s their use had largely been supplanted by higher-level languages in the search for improved programming productivity.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Today, assembly language is still used for direct hardware manipulation, access to specialized processor instructions, or to address critical performance issues.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Typical uses are device drivers, low-level embedded systems, and real-time systems (see § Current usage).
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Numerous programs were written entirely in assembly language.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] The Burroughs MCP (1961) was the first computer for which an operating system was not developed entirely in assembly language; it was written in Executive Systems Problem Oriented Language (ESPOL), an Algol dialect.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Many commercial applications were written in assembly language as well, including a large amount of the IBM mainframe software developed by large corporations.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] COBOL, FORTRAN and some PL/I eventually displaced assembly language, although a number of large organizations retained assembly-language application infrastructures well into the 1990s.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the primary development language for 8-bit home computers such as the Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, ZX Spectrum, and Commodore 64.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Interpreted BASIC on these systems did not offer maximum execution speed and full use of facilities to take full advantage of the available hardware.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the default choice for programming 8-bit consoles such as the Atari 2600 and Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Key software for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS, Turbo Pascal, and the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet was written in assembly language.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] As computer speed grew exponentially, assembly language became a tool for speeding up parts of programs, such as the rendering of *Doom*, rather than a dominant development language.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] In the 1990s, assembly language was used to maximise performance from systems such as the Sega Saturn, and as the primary language for arcade hardware using the TMS34010 integrated CPU/GPU such as *Mortal Kombat* and *NBA Jam*.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] There has been debate over the usefulness and performance of assembly language relative to high-level languages.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Although assembly language has specific niche uses where it is important (see below), there are other tools for optimization.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] As of July 2017, the TIOBE index of programming language popularity ranks assembly language at 11, ahead of Visual Basic, for example.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Assembler can be used to optimize for speed or optimize for size.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] In the case of speed optimization, modern optimizing compilers are claimed to render high-level languages into code that can run as fast as hand-written assembly, despite some counter-examples.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] The complexity of modern processors and memory sub-systems makes effective optimization increasingly difficult for compilers and assembly programmers alike.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Increasing processor performance has meant that most CPUs sit idle most of the time, with delays caused by predictable bottlenecks such as cache misses, I/O operations and paging, making raw code execution speed a non-issue for many programmers.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language is still taught in most computer science and electronic engineering programs.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Although few programmers today regularly work with assembly language as a tool, the underlying concepts remain important.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Such fundamental topics as binary arithmetic, memory allocation, stack processing, character set encoding, interrupt processing, and compiler design would be hard to study in detail without a grasp of how a computer operates at the hardware level.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Since a computer's behaviour is fundamentally defined by its instruction set, the logical way to learn such concepts is to study an assembly language.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Most modern computers have similar instruction sets.
[src:gcc-internals/assembly-language-p02] Therefore, studying a single assembly language is sufficient to learn the basic concepts, recognize situations where the use of assembly language might be appropriate, and to see how efficient executable code can be created from high-level languages.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] A **cross compiler** is a compiler capable of creating executable code for a platform other than the one on which the compiler is running.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] For example, a compiler that runs on a PC but generates code that runs on Android devices is a cross compiler.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] A cross compiler is useful to compile code for multiple platforms from one development host.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Direct compilation on the target platform might be infeasible, for example on embedded systems with limited computing resources.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Cross compilers are distinct from source-to-source compilers.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] A cross compiler is for cross-platform software generation of machine code, while a source-to-source compiler translates from one coding language to another in text code.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The fundamental use of a cross compiler is to separate the build environment from target environment.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Use of virtual machines (such as Java's JVM) resolves some of the reasons for which cross compilers were developed.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The virtual machine paradigm allows the same compiler output to be used across multiple target systems, although this is not always ideal because virtual machines are often slower and the compiled program can only be run on computers with that virtual machine.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The **Canadian Cross** is a technique for building cross compilers for other machines, where the original machine is much slower or less convenient than the target.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Given three machines A, B, and C, one uses machine A (e.g. running Windows XP on an IA-32 processor) to build a cross compiler that runs on machine B (e.g. running macOS on an x86-64 processor) to create executables for machine C (e.g. running Android on an ARM processor).
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The practical advantage in this example is that Machine A is slow but has a proprietary compiler, while Machine B is fast but has no compiler at all, and Machine C is impractically slow to be used for compilation.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The end-result cross compiler (4) will not be able to run on build machine A; instead it would run on machine B to compile an application into executable code that would then be copied to machine C and executed on machine C.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] For instance, NetBSD provides a POSIX Unix shell script named `build.sh` which will first build its own toolchain with the host's compiler; this, in turn, will be used to build the cross compiler which will be used to build the whole system.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The term **Canadian Cross** came about because at the time that these issues were under discussion, Canada had three national political parties.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] GCC, a free software collection of compilers, can be set up to cross compile.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] It supports many platforms and languages.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] GCC requires that a compiled copy of binutils is available for each targeted platform.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Especially important is the GNU Assembler.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Therefore, binutils first has to be compiled correctly with the switch `--target=some-target` sent to the configure script.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] GCC also has to be configured with the same `--target` option.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Cross-compiling GCC requires that a portion of the *target platform'*s C standard library be available on the *host platform*.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The programmer may choose to compile the full C library, but this choice could be unreliable.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The alternative is to use newlib, which is a small C library containing only the most essential components required to compile C source code.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The GNU Autotools packages (i.e. autoconf, automake, and libtool) use the notion of a *build platform*, a *host platform*, and a *target platform*.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The *build platform* is where the compiler is actually compiled.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] In most cases, build should be left undefined (it will default from host).
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The *host platform* is always where the output artifacts from the compiler will be executed whether the output is another compiler or not.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The *target platform* is used when cross-compiling cross compilers, it represents what type of object code the package will produce; otherwise the *target platform* setting is irrelevant.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] For example, consider cross-compiling a video game that will run on a Dreamcast.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The machine where the game is compiled is the *build platform* while the Dreamcast is the *host platform*.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The names *host* and *target* are relative to the compiler being used and shifted like *son* and *grandson*.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Another method popularly used by embedded Linux developers involves the combination of GCC compilers with specialized sandboxes like Scratchbox and Scratchbox 2, or PRoot.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] These tools create a "chrooted" sandbox where the programmer can build up necessary tools, libc, and libraries without having to set extra paths.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Facilities are also provided to "deceive" the runtime so that it "believes" it is actually running on the intended target CPU (such as an ARM architecture); this allows configuration scripts and the like to run without error.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Scratchbox runs more slowly by comparison to "non-chrooted" methods, and most tools that are on the host must be moved into Scratchbox to function.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Manx Software Systems, of Shrewsbury, New Jersey, produced C compilers beginning in the 1980s targeted at professional developers for a variety of platforms up to and including IBM PC compatibles and Macs.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Manx's Aztec C programming language was available for a variety of platforms including MS-DOS, Apple II, DOS 3.3 and ProDOS, Commodore 64, Mac 68k and Amiga.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] From the 1980s and continuing throughout the 1990s until Manx Software Systems disappeared, the MS-DOS version of Aztec C was offered both as a native mode compiler or as a cross compiler for other platforms with different processors including the Commodore 64 and Apple II.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Internet distributions still exist for Aztec C including their MS-DOS based cross compilers.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Manx's Aztec C86, their native mode 8086 MS-DOS compiler, was also a cross compiler.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Although it did not compile code for a different processor like their Aztec C65 6502 cross compilers for the Commodore 64 and Apple II, it created binary executables for then-legacy operating systems for the 16-bit 8086 family of processors.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] When the IBM PC was first introduced it was available with a choice of operating systems, CP/M-86 and PC DOS being two of them.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Aztec C86 was provided with link libraries for generating code for both IBM PC operating systems.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Throughout the 1980s later versions of Aztec C86 (3.xx, 4.xx and 5.xx) added support for MS-DOS "transitory" versions 1 and 2 and which were less robust than the "baseline" MS-DOS version 3 and later which Aztec C86 targeted until its demise.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Finally, Aztec C86 provided C language developers with the ability to produce ROM-able "HEX" code which could then be transferred using a ROM burner directly to an 8086 based processor.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Paravirtualization may be more common today but the practice of creating low-level ROM code was more common per-capita during those years when device driver development was often done by application programmers for individual applications, and new devices amounted to a cottage industry.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] It was not uncommon for application programmers to interface directly with hardware without support from the manufacturer.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] This practice was similar to Embedded Systems Development today.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Thomas Fenwick and James Goodnow II were the two principal developers of Aztec-C.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Fenwick later became notable as the author of the Microsoft Windows CE kernel or NK ("New Kernel") as it was then called.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Microsoft C (MSC) has a shorter history than others dating back to the 1980s.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The first Microsoft C Compilers were made by the same company who made Lattice C and were rebranded by Microsoft as their own, until MSC 4 was released, which was the first version that Microsoft produced themselves.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] In 1987, many developers started switching to Microsoft C, and many more would follow throughout the development of Microsoft Windows to its present state.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Products like Clipper and later Clarion emerged that offered easy database application development by using cross language techniques, allowing part of their programs to be compiled with Microsoft C.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Borland C (California company) was available for purchase years before Microsoft released its first C product.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] C programs had long been linked with modules written in assembly language.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Most C compilers (even current compilers) offer an assembly language pass (that can be tweaked for efficiency then linked to the rest of the program after assembling).
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] By 1987, with the release of MSC 5.1, Microsoft offered a cross language development environment for MS-DOS.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] 16-bit binary object code written in assembly language (MASM) and Microsoft's other languages including QuickBASIC, Pascal, and Fortran could be linked together into one program, in a process they called "Mixed Language Programming" and now "InterLanguage Calling".
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] If BASIC was used in this mix, the main program needed to be in BASIC to support the internal runtime system that compiled BASIC required for garbage collection and its other managed operations that simulated a BASIC interpreter like QBasic in MS-DOS.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The calling convention for C code, in particular, was to pass parameters in "reverse order" on the stack and return values on the stack rather than in a processor register.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] There were other programming rules to make all the languages work together, but this particular rule persisted through the cross language development that continued throughout Windows 16- and 32-bit versions and in the development of programs for OS/2, and which persists to this day.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] It is known as the Pascal calling convention.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Another type of cross compilation that Microsoft C was used for during this time was in retail applications that require handheld devices like the Symbol Technologies PDT3100 (used to take inventory), which provided a link library targeted at an 8088 based barcode reader.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The application was built on the host computer then transferred to the handheld device (via a serial cable) where it was run, similar to what is done today for that same market using Windows Mobile by companies like Motorola, who bought Symbol.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Throughout the 1990s and beginning with MSC 6 (their first ANSI C compliant compiler) Microsoft re-focused their C compilers on the emerging Windows market, and also on OS/2 and in the development of GUI programs.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Mixed language compatibility remained through MSC 6 on the MS-DOS side, but the API for Microsoft Windows 3.0 and 3.1 was written in MSC 6.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] MSC 6 was also extended to provide support for 32-bit assemblies and support for the emerging Windows for Workgroups and Windows NT which would form the foundation for Windows XP.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] A programming practice called a thunk was introduced to allow passing between 16- and 32-bit programs that took advantage of runtime binding (dynamic linking) rather than the static binding that was favoured in monolithic 16-bit MS-DOS applications.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Static binding is still favoured by some native code developers but does not generally provide the degree of code reuse required by newer best practices like the Capability Maturity Model (CMM).
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] MS-DOS support was still provided with the release of Microsoft's first C++ Compiler, MSC 7, which was backwardly compatible with the C programming language and MS-DOS and supported both 16- and 32-bit code generation.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] MS-DOS and 16-bit code generation support continued until MSC 8.00c which was bundled with Microsoft C++ and Microsoft Application Studio 1.5, the forerunner of Microsoft Visual Studio which is the cross development environment that Microsoft provide today.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] MSC 12 was released with Microsoft Visual Studio 6 and no longer provided support for MS-DOS 16-bit binaries, instead providing support for 32-bit console applications, but provided support for Windows 95 and Windows 98 code generation as well as for Windows NT.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Link libraries were available for other processors that ran Microsoft Windows; a practice that Microsoft continues to this day.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] MSC 13 was released with Visual Studio 2003, and MSC 14 was released with Visual Studio 2005, both of which still produce code for older systems like Windows 95, but which will produce code for several target platforms including the mobile market and the ARM architecture.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] In 2001 Microsoft developed the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which formed the core for their .NET Framework compiler in the Visual Studio IDE.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] This layer on the operating system which is in the API allows the mixing of development languages compiled across platforms that run the Windows operating system.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The .NET Framework runtime and CLR provide a mapping layer to the core routines for the processor and the devices on the target computer.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The command-line C compiler in Visual Studio will compile native code for a variety of processors and can be used to build the core routines themselves.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Runtime libraries, such as Mono, provide compatibility for cross-compiled .NET programs to other operating systems, such as Linux.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Libraries like Qt and its predecessors including XVT provide source code level cross development capability with other platforms, while still using Microsoft C to build the Windows versions.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Other compilers like MinGW have also become popular in this area since they are more directly compatible with the Unixes that comprise the non-Windows side of software development allowing those developers to target all platforms using a familiar build environment.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Free Pascal was developed from the beginning as a cross compiler.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The compiler executable (ppcXXX where XXX is a target architecture) is capable of producing executables (or just object files if no internal linker exists, or even just assembly files if no internal assembler exists) for all OS of the same architecture.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] For example, ppc386 is capable of producing executables for i386-linux, i386-win32, i386-go32v2 (DOS) and all other OSes (see ).
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] For compiling to another architecture, however, a cross architecture version of the compiler must be built first.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The resulting compiler executable would have additional 'ross' before the target architecture in its name. i.e. if the compiler is built to target x64, then the executable would be ppcrossx64.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] To compile for a chosen architecture-OS, the compiler switch (for the compiler driver fpc) -P and -T can be used.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] This is also done when cross-compiling the compiler itself, but is set via make option CPU_TARGET and OS_TARGET.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] GNU assembler and linker for the target platform is required if Free Pascal does not yet have internal version of the tools for the target platform.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] Clang is natively a cross compiler, at build time you can select which architectures you want Clang to be able to target by using the `-target` flag.
[src:gcc-internals/cross-compiler] The heterogenous system Plan 9 and its toolchain does not distinguish between cross and native compilation.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The **GNU Compiler Collection** (**GCC**; formerly **GNU C Compiler**) is a collection of compilers from the GNU Project that support various programming languages, hardware architectures, and operating systems.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The Free Software Foundation (FSF) distributes GCC as free software under the GNU General Public License (GNU GPL).
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC is a key component of the GNU toolchain which is used for most projects related to GNU and the Linux kernel.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] With roughly 15 million lines of code in 2019, GCC is one of the largest free programs in existence.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] It has played an important role in the growth of free software, as both a tool and an example.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] When it was first released in 1987 by Richard Stallman, GCC 1.0 was named the *GNU C Compiler* since it only handled the C programming language.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] It was extended to compile C++ in December of that year.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Front ends were later developed for Objective-C, Objective-C++, Fortran, Ada, Go, D, Modula-2, Rust, COBOL, and ALGOL 68 among others.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The OpenMP and OpenACC specifications are also supported in the C and C++ compilers.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] As well as being the official compiler of the GNU operating system, GCC has been adopted as the standard compiler by many other modern Unix-like computer operating systems, including most Linux distributions.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Most BSD family operating systems also switched to GCC shortly after its release, although since then, FreeBSD and Apple macOS have moved to the Clang compiler, largely due to licensing reasons.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC can also compile code for Windows, Android, iOS, Solaris, HP-UX, AIX, and MS-DOS compatible operating systems.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC has been ported to more platforms and instruction set architectures than any other compiler, and is widely deployed as a tool in the development of both free and proprietary software.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC is also available for many embedded systems, including ARM-based and Power ISA-based chips.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] In late 1983, in an effort to bootstrap the GNU operating system, Richard Stallman asked Andrew S.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Tanenbaum, the author of the Amsterdam Compiler Kit (also known as the *Free University* *Compiler Kit*), for permission to use that software for GNU.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] When Tanenbaum advised him that the compiler itself was not free, but rather only the university, Stallman decided to work on a different compiler.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] His initial plan was to rewrite an existing compiler from Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory for the Pastel language, written in Pastel, with some help from Len Tower and others.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Stallman wrote a new C front end for the Livermore compiler, but then realized that it required megabytes of stack space, an impossibility on a 68000 Unix system that didn't allow more than 64 KB of stack space, and concluded he would have to write a new compiler from scratch.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] None of the Pastel compiler code ended up in GCC, though Stallman did use the C front end he had written in Pastel.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC was first released March 22, 1987, available by FTP from MIT.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Stallman was listed as the author but cited others for their contributions, including Tower for "parts of the parser, RTL generator, RTL definitions, and of the Vax machine description", Jack Davidson and Christopher W.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Fraser for the idea of using RTL as an intermediate language, and Paul Rubin for writing most of the preprocessor.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Described as the "first free software hit" by Peter H.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Salus, the GNU compiler arrived just at the time when Sun Microsystems was unbundling its development tools from its operating system, selling them separately at a higher combined price than the previous bundle, which led many of Sun's users to buy or download GCC instead of the vendor's tools.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] While Stallman considered GNU Emacs as his main project, by 1990 GCC supported thirteen computer architectures, was outperforming several vendor compilers, and was used commercially by several companies.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] As GCC was licensed under the GPL, programmers wanting to work in other directions—particularly those writing interfaces for languages other than C—were free to develop their own fork of the compiler, provided they meet the GPL's terms, including its requirements to distribute source code.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Multiple forks proved inefficient and unwieldy, however, and the difficulty in getting work accepted by the official GCC project was greatly frustrating for many, as the project favored stability over new features.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The FSF kept such close control on what was added to the official version of GCC 2.x (developed since 1992) that GCC was used as one example of the "cathedral" development model in Eric S.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Raymond's essay *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] In 1997, a group of developers formed the *Experimental/Enhanced GNU Compiler System (EGCS)* to merge several experimental forks into a single project.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The basis of the merger was a development snapshot of GCC (taken around the 2.7.2 and later followed up to 2.8.1 release).
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Mergers included g77 (Fortran), PGCC (P5 Pentium-optimized GCC), many C++ improvements, and many new architectures and operating system variants.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] With the release of GCC 2.95 in July 1999 the two projects were once again united.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC has since been maintained by a varied group of programmers from around the world under the direction of a steering committee.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC 3 (2002) removed a front-end for CHILL due to a lack of maintenance.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Before version 4.0 the Fortran front end was `g77`, which only supported FORTRAN 77, but later was dropped in favor of the new GNU Fortran front end that supports Fortran 95 and large parts of Fortran 2003 and Fortran 2008 as well.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] As of version 4.8, GCC is implemented in C++.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Support for Cilk Plus existed from GCC 5 to GCC 7.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC has been ported to a wide variety of instruction set architectures, and is widely deployed as a tool in the development of both free and proprietary software.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC is also available for many embedded systems, including Symbian (called *gcce*), ARM-based, and Power ISA-based chips.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The compiler can target a wide variety of platforms, including video game consoles such as the PlayStation 2, Cell SPE of PlayStation 3, and Dreamcast.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] It has been ported to "more than 60 platforms".
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Versions prior to GCC 7 also supported Java (`gcj`), allowing compilation of Java to native machine code.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Third-party front ends exist for many languages, such as Pascal (`gpc`), Mercury, Modula-3, VHDL (`GHDL`) and PL/I.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] A few experimental branches exist to support additional languages, such as the GCC UPC compiler for Unified Parallel C.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The default target for C++ since GCC 15.1 is *gnu++20*, a superset of C++20, and the default target for C since GCC 15 is *gnu23*, a superset of C23, with strict standard support also available.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC also provides experimental support for C2Y, C++23, and C++26.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC's external interface follows Unix conventions.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Users invoke a language-specific driver program (`gcc` for C, `g++` for C++, etc.), which interprets command arguments, calls the actual compiler, runs the assembler on the output, and then optionally runs the linker to produce a complete executable binary.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Each of the language compilers is a separate program that reads source code and outputs machine code.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] A per-language front end parses the source code in that language and produces an abstract syntax tree ("tree" for short).
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] These are, if necessary, converted to the middle end's input representation, called *GENERIC* form; the middle end then gradually transforms the program towards its final form.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Compiler optimizations and static code analysis techniques (such as FORTIFY_SOURCE, a compiler directive that attempts to discover some buffer overflows) are applied to the code.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] These work on multiple representations, mostly the architecture-independent GIMPLE representation and the architecture-dependent RTL representation.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Finally, machine code is produced using architecture-specific pattern matching originally based on an algorithm of Jack Davidson and Chris Fraser.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC was written primarily in C except for parts of the Ada front end.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The distribution includes the standard libraries for Ada and C++ whose code is mostly written in those languages.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] On some platforms, the distribution also includes a low-level runtime library, **libgcc**, written in a combination of machine-independent C and processor-specific machine code, designed primarily to handle arithmetic operations that the target processor cannot perform directly.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC uses many additional tools in its build, many of which are installed by default by many Unix and Linux distributions (but which, normally, aren't present in Windows installations), including Perl, Flex, Bison, and other common tools.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] In addition, it currently requires three additional libraries to be present in order to build: GMP, MPC, and MPFR.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] In May 2010, the GCC steering committee decided to allow use of a C++ compiler to compile GCC.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The compiler was intended to be written mostly in C plus a subset of features from C++.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] In particular, this was decided so that GCC's developers could use the destructors and generics features of C++.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] In August 2012, the GCC steering committee announced that GCC now uses C++ as its implementation language.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] This means that to build GCC from sources, a C++ compiler is required that understands ISO/IEC C++03 standard.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] On May 18, 2020, GCC moved away from ISO/IEC C++03 standard to ISO/IEC C++11 standard (i.e. needed to compile, bootstrap, the compiler itself; by default it however compiles later versions of C++).
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Each front end uses a parser to produce the abstract syntax tree of a given source file.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Due to the syntax tree abstraction, source files of any of the different supported languages can be processed by the same back end.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC started out using LALR parsers generated with Bison, but gradually switched to hand-written recursive-descent parsers for C++ in 2004, and for C and Objective-C in 2006.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] As of 2021 all front ends use hand-written recursive-descent parsers.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Until GCC 4.0, the tree representation of the program was not fully independent of the processor being targeted.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The meaning of a tree was somewhat different for different language front ends, and front ends could provide their own tree codes.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] This was simplified with the introduction of GENERIC and GIMPLE, two new forms of language-independent trees that were introduced with the advent of GCC 4.0.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GENERIC is more complex, based on the GCC 3.x Java front end's intermediate representation.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] GIMPLE is a simplified GENERIC, in which various constructs are *lowered* to multiple GIMPLE instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The C, C++, and Java front ends produce GENERIC directly in the front end.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Other front ends instead have different intermediate representations after parsing and convert these to GENERIC.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] In either case, the so-called "gimplifier" then converts this more complex form into the simpler SSA-based GIMPLE form that is the common language for a large number of language- and architecture-independent global (function scope) optimizations.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The middle stage of GCC does all of the code analysis and optimization, working independently of both the compiled language and the target architecture, starting from the GENERIC representation and expanding it to register transfer language (RTL).
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The GENERIC representation contains only the subset of the imperative programming constructs optimized by the middle end.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] In transforming the source code to GIMPLE, complex expressions are split into a three-address code using temporary variables.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] This representation was inspired by the SIMPLE representation proposed in the McCAT compiler by Laurie J.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Hendren for simplifying the analysis and optimization of imperative programs.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The exact set of GCC optimizations varies from release to release as it develops, but includes the standard algorithms, such as loop optimization, jump threading, common subexpression elimination, instruction scheduling, and so forth.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The RTL optimizations are of less importance with the addition of global SSA-based optimizations on GIMPLE trees, as RTL optimizations have a much more limited scope, and have less high-level information.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Some of these optimizations performed at this level include dead-code elimination, partial-redundancy elimination, global value numbering, sparse conditional constant propagation, and scalar replacement of aggregates.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Array dependence based optimizations such as automatic vectorization and automatic parallelization are also performed.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Profile-guided optimization is also possible.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] The GCC project includes an implementation of the C++ Standard Library called libstdc++, licensed under the GPLv3 License with an exception to link non-GPL-compatible applications when sources are built with GCC.
[src:gcc-internals/gnu-compiler-collection] Since GCC Version 3, the C++ ABI is based on the ABI published by Intel for the Itanium C++ ABI.
