[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Some pervasive algorithms such as matrix multiplication have very poor cache behavior and excessive memory accesses.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Loop nest optimization increases the number of cache hits by operating over small blocks and by using a loop interchange.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Loop reversal reverses the order in which values are assigned to the index variable.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Furthermore, on some architectures, loop reversal contributes to smaller code, as when the loop index is being decremented, the condition that needs to be met for the running program to exit the loop is a comparison with zero.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] This is often a special, parameter-less instruction, unlike a comparison with a number, which needs the number to compare to.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Therefore, the amount of bytes needed to store the parameter is saved by using the loop reversal.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Additionally, if the comparison number exceeds the size of word of the platform, in standard loop order, multiple instructions would need to be executed to evaluate the comparison, which is not the case with loop reversal.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Unrolling duplicates the body of the loop multiple times, to decrease the number of times the loop condition is tested and the number of jumps; tests and jumps can hurt performance by impairing the instruction pipeline.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Completely unrolling a loop eliminates all overhead, but requires that the number of iterations be known at compile time.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Loop splitting attempts to simplify a loop or eliminate dependencies by breaking it into multiple loops that have the same bodies but iterate over different contiguous portions of the index range.
