[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Interprocedural optimization works on the entire program, across procedure and file boundaries.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] It works tightly with intraprocedural counterparts, carried out with the cooperation of a local part and a global part.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Typical interprocedural optimizations are procedure inlining, interprocedural dead-code elimination, interprocedural constant propagation, and procedure reordering.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] As usual, the compiler needs to perform interprocedural analysis before its actual optimizations.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Interprocedural analyses include alias analysis, array access analysis, and the construction of a call graph.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Interprocedural optimization is common in modern commercial compilers from SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] For a long time, the open source GCC was criticized for a lack of powerful interprocedural analysis and optimizations, though this is now improving.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Another open-source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Due to the extra time and space required by interprocedural analysis, most compilers do not perform it by default.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Users must use compiler options explicitly to tell the compiler to enable interprocedural analysis and other expensive optimizations.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] There can be a wide range of optimizations that a compiler can perform, ranging from simple and straightforward optimizations that take little compilation time to elaborate and complex optimizations that involve considerable amounts of compilation time.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] By the 2000s, it was common for compilers, such as Clang, to have several compiler command options that could affect a variety of optimization choices, starting with the familiar `-O2` switch.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] An approach to isolating optimization is the use of so-called post-pass optimizers (some commercial versions of which date back to mainframe software of the late 1970s).
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] These tools take the executable output by an optimizing compiler and optimize it even further.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Post-pass optimizers usually work on the assembly language or machine code level (in contrast with compilers that optimize intermediate representations of programs).
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] One such example is the Portable C Compiler (PCC) of the 1980s, which had an optional pass that would perform post-optimizations on the generated assembly code.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Another consideration is that optimization algorithms are complicated and, especially when being used to compile large, complex programming languages, can contain bugs that introduce errors in the generated code or cause internal errors during compilation.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Compiler errors of any kind can be disconcerting to the user, but especially so in this case, since it may not be clear that the optimization logic is at fault.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] In the case of internal errors, the problem can be partially ameliorated by a "fail-safe" programming technique in which the optimization logic in the compiler is coded such that a failure is trapped, a warning message issued, and the rest of the compilation proceeds to successful completion.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Early compilers of the 1960s were often primarily concerned with simply compiling code correctly or efficiently, such that compile times were a major concern.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] One notable early optimizing compiler was the IBM FORTRAN H compiler of the late 1960s.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] Another of the earliest and important optimizing compilers, that pioneered several advanced techniques, was that for BLISS (1970), which was described in *The Design of an Optimizing Compiler* (1975).
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] By the late 1980s, optimizing compilers were sufficiently effective that programming in assembly language declined.
[src:gcc-internals/optimizing-compiler] This co-evolved with the development of RISC chips and advanced processor features such as superscalar processors, out-of-order execution, and speculative execution, which were designed to be targeted by optimizing compilers rather than by human-written assembly code.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In compiler optimization, **register allocation** is the process of assigning local automatic variables and expression results to a limited number of processor registers.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Register allocation can happen over a basic block (*local register allocation*), over a whole function/procedure (*global register allocation*), or across function boundaries traversed via call-graph (*interprocedural register allocation*).
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] When done per function/procedure the calling convention may require insertion of save/restore around each call-site.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In many programming languages, the programmer may use any number of variables.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] The computer can quickly read and write registers in the CPU, so the computer program runs faster when more variables can be in the CPU's registers.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Also, sometimes code accessing registers is more compact, so the code is smaller, and can be fetched faster if it uses registers rather than memory.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] However, the number of registers is limited.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Therefore, when the compiler is translating code to machine-language, it must decide how to allocate variables to the limited number of registers in the CPU.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Not all variables are in use (or "live") at the same time, so, over the lifetime of a program, a given register may be used to hold different variables.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] However, two variables in use at the *same* time cannot be assigned to the same register without corrupting one of the variables.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] If there are not enough registers to hold all the variables, some variables may be moved to and from RAM.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This process is called "spilling" the registers.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Over the lifetime of a program, a variable can be both spilled and stored in registers: this variable is then considered as "split".
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Accessing RAM is significantly slower than accessing registers and so a compiled program runs slower.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Therefore, an optimizing compiler aims to assign as many variables to registers as possible.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] A high "Register pressure" is a technical term that means that more spills and reloads are needed; it is defined by Braun et al. as "the number of simultaneously live variables at an instruction".
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In addition, some computer designs cache frequently-accessed registers.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] So, programs can be further optimized by assigning the same register to a source and destination of a `move` instruction whenever possible.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This is especially important if the compiler is using an intermediate representation such as static single-assignment form (SSA).
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In particular, when SSA is not fully optimized it can artificially generate additional `move` instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Register allocation consists therefore of choosing where to store the variables at runtime, i.e. inside or outside registers.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] If the variable is to be stored in registers, then the allocator needs to determine in which register(s) this variable will be stored.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Eventually, another challenge is to determine the duration for which a variable should stay at the same location.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] A register allocator, disregarding the chosen allocation strategy, can rely on a set of core actions to address these challenges.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This action consists of increasing the number of move instructions between registers, i.e. make a variable live in different registers during its lifetime, instead of one.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This occurs in the split live range approach.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This action consists of assigning a register to a variable.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This action consists of limiting the number of moves between registers, thus limiting the total number of instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] For instance, by identifying a variable live across different methods, and storing it into one register during its whole lifetime.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Many register allocation approaches optimize for one or more specific categories of actions.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Register allocation raises several problems that can be tackled (or avoided) by different register allocation approaches.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In some architectures, assigning a value to one register can affect the value of another: this is called aliasing.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] architecture has four general purpose 32-bit registers that can also be used as 16-bit or 8-bit registers.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In this case, assigning a 32-bit value to the eax register will affect the value of the al register.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This problem is an act to force some variables to be assigned to particular registers.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] , parameters are commonly passed in R3-R10 and the return value is passed in R3.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This NP-completeness is entirely dependent upon exactly how the problem is structured.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] portion of the register allocation problem can be solved in linear time.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] What causes the general graph coloring problem to be NP-complete and what causes the some versions of the register allocation problem to be NP-complete are distinct.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Register allocation can happen over a basic block of code: it is said to be "local", and was first mentioned by Horwitz et al.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] As basic blocks do not contain branches, the allocation process is thought to be fast, because the management of control-flow graph merge points in register allocation reveals itself a time-consuming operation.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] However, this approach is thought not to produce as optimized code as the "global" approach, which operates over the whole compilation unit (a method or procedure for instance).
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Graph-coloring allocation is the predominant approach to solve register allocation.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In this approach, nodes in the graph represent live ranges (variables, temporaries, virtual/symbolic registers) that are candidates for register allocation.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Edges connect live ranges that interfere, i.e., live ranges that are simultaneously live at at least one program point.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Register allocation then reduces to the graph coloring problem in which colors (registers) are assigned to the nodes such that two nodes connected by an edge do not receive the same color.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Using liveness analysis, an interference graph can be built.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] The interference graph, which is an Interval graph where the nodes are the program's variables, is used to model which variables cannot be allocated to the same register.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] **Build**: build the interference graph.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] **Coalesce**: merge the live ranges of non-interfering variables related by copy instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] **Spill cost**: compute the spill cost of each variable.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This assesses the impact of mapping a variable to memory on the speed of the final program.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] **Spill Code**: insert spill instructions, i.e. loads and stores to commute values between registers and memory.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] **Select**: assign a register to each variable.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] The graph-coloring allocation has three major drawbacks.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] First, it relies on graph-coloring, which is an NP-complete problem, to decide which variables are spilled.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Although finding a minimal coloring for general graphs is indeed an NP-complete problem, minimal coloring of Interval graphs (including interference graphs) can be done in linear time (see Linear scan below); Therefore, this technique does not full utilize the problem's assumptions.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Second, unless live-range splitting is used, evicted variables are spilled everywhere: store instructions are inserted as early as possible, i.e., just after variable definitions; load instructions are respectively inserted late, just before variable use.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Third, a variable that is not spilled is kept in the same register throughout its whole lifetime.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] On the other hand, a single register name may appear in multiple register classes, where a class is a set of register names that are interchangeable in a particular role.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Then, multiple register names may be aliases for a single hardware register.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Finally, graph coloring is an aggressive technique for allocating registers, but is computationally expensive due to its use of the interference graph, which can have a worst-case size that is quadratic in the number of live ranges.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] The traditional formulation of graph-coloring register allocation implicitly assumes a single bank of non-overlapping general-purpose registers and does not handle irregular architectural features like overlapping registers pairs, special purpose registers and multiple register banks.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] One later improvement of Chaitin-style graph-coloring approach was found by Briggs et al.: it is called conservative coalescing.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This improvement adds a criterion to decide when two live ranges can be merged.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Mainly, in addition to the non-interfering requirements, two variables can only be coalesced if their merging will not cause further spilling.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Briggs et al. introduces a second improvement to Chaitin's works which is biased coloring.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Biased coloring tries to assign the same color in the graph-coloring to live range that are copy related.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Linear scan is another global register allocation approach.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] It was first proposed by Poletto et al. in 1999.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In this approach, the code is not turned into a graph.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Instead, all the variables are linearly scanned to determine their live range, represented as an interval.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Once the live ranges of all variables have been figured out, the intervals are traversed chronologically.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Although this traversal could help identifying variables whose live ranges interfere, no interference graph is being built and the variables are allocated in a greedy way.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] The motivation for this approach is speed; not in terms of execution time of the generated code, but in terms of time spent in code generation.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Typically, the standard graph coloring approaches produce quality code, but have a significant overhead, the used graph coloring algorithm having a quadratic cost.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Owing to this feature, linear scan is the approach currently used in several JIT compilers, like the Hotspot client compiler, V8, Jikes RVM, and the Android Runtime (ART).
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] The Hotspot server compiler uses graph coloring for its superior code.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] However, the linear scan presents two major drawbacks.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] First, due to its greedy aspect, it does not take lifetime holes into account, i.e.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] "ranges where the value of the variable is not needed".
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Besides, a spilled variable will stay spilled for its entire lifetime.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Many other research works followed up on the Poletto's linear scan algorithm.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Traub et al., for instance, proposed an algorithm called second-chance binpacking aiming at generating code of better quality.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In this approach, spilled variables get the opportunity to be stored later in a register by using a different heuristic from the one used in the standard linear scan algorithm.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Instead of using live intervals, the algorithm relies on live ranges, meaning that if a range needs to be spilled, it is not necessary to spill all the other ranges corresponding to this variable.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Linear scan allocation was also adapted to take advantage from the SSA form: the properties of this intermediate representation simplify the allocation algorithm and allow lifetime holes to be computed directly.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] First, the time spent in data-flow graph analysis, aimed at building the lifetime intervals, is reduced, namely because variables are unique.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] It consequently produces shorter live intervals, because each new assignment corresponds to a new live interval.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] To avoid modeling intervals and liveness holes, Rogers showed a simplification called future-active sets that successfully removed intervals for 80% of instructions.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In the context of register allocation, coalescing is the act of merging variable-to-variable move operations by allocating those two variables to the same location.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] The coalescing operation takes place after the interference graph is built.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Once two nodes have been coalesced, they must get the same color and be allocated to the same register, once the copy operation becomes unnecessary.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Doing coalescing might have both positive and negative impacts on the colorability of the interference graph.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] For example, one negative impact that coalescing could have on graph inference colorability is when two nodes are coalesced, as the result node will have a union of the edges of those being coalesced.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] A positive impact of coalescing on inference graph colorability is, for example, when a node interferes with both nodes being coalesced, the degree of the node is reduced by one which leads to improving the overall colorability of the interference graph.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] It was first introduced in Chaitin's original register allocator.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This heuristic aims at coalescing any non-interfering, copy-related nodes.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] From the perspective of copy elimination, this heuristic has the best results.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] On the other hand, aggressive coalescing could impact the colorability of the inference graph.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] It mainly uses the same heuristic as aggressive coalescing but it merges moves if, and only if, it does not compromise the colorability of the interference graph.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] It removes one particular move at the time, while keeping the colorability of the graph.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] It is based on aggressive coalescing, but if the inference graph colorability is compromised, then it gives up as few moves as possible.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Some other register allocation approaches do not limit to one technique to optimize register's use.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Cavazos et al., for instance, proposed a solution where it is possible to use both the linear scan and the graph coloring algorithms.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In this approach, the choice between one or the other solution is determined dynamically: first, a machine learning algorithm is used "offline", that is to say not at runtime, to build a heuristic function that determines which allocation algorithm needs to be used.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] The heuristic function is then used at runtime; in light of the code behavior, the allocator can then choose between one of the two available algorithms.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Trace register allocation is a recent approach developed by Eisl et al.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This technique handles the allocation locally: it relies on dynamic profiling data to determine which branches will be the most frequently used in a given control flow graph.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] It then infers a set of "traces" (i.e. code segments) in which the merge point is ignored in favor of the most used branch.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Each trace is then independently processed by the allocator.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] This approach can be considered as hybrid because it is possible to use different register allocation algorithms between the different traces.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Split allocation is another register allocation technique that combines different approaches, usually considered as opposite.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] For instance, the hybrid allocation technique can be considered as split because the first heuristic building stage is performed offline, and the heuristic use is performed online.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Diouf et al. proposed an allocation technique relying both on offline and online behaviors, namely static and dynamic compilation.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] During the offline stage, an optimal spill set is first gathered using Integer Linear Programming.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Then, live ranges are annotated using the `compressAnnotation` algorithm which relies on the previously identified optimal spill set.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Register allocation is performed afterwards during the online stage, based on the data collected in the offline phase.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] In 2007, Bouchez et al. suggested as well to split the register allocation in different stages, having one stage dedicated to spilling, and one dedicated to coloring and coalescing.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Several metrics have been used to assess the performance of one register allocation technique against the other.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Register allocation has typically to deal with a trade-off between code quality, i.e. code that executes quickly, and analysis overhead, i.e. the time spent determining analyzing the source code to generate code with optimized register allocation.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] From this perspective, execution time of the generated code and time spent in liveness analysis are relevant metrics to compare the different techniques.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] Once relevant metrics have been chosen, the code on which the metrics will be applied should be available and relevant to the problem, either by reflecting the behavior of real-world application, or by being relevant to the particular problem the algorithm wants to address.
[src:gcc-internals/register-allocation] The more recent articles about register allocation uses especially the Dacapo benchmark suite.
